BT
/F1 12 Tf
72 760 Td
16 TL
(1. Motivation) Tj
T*
(The original design placed most behaviour in the Bank class. Bank stored global lists and dictionaries, managed branch opening times, moved staff between branches, changed account balances, applied interest, closed accounts, and reached through Payroll to update pay schedules. This made Bank a god class: it knew too much about the internal data and behaviour of other objects.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The aim of the refactoring was to redistribute responsibilities so behaviour sits closer to the data it changes. This follows the reengineering patterns from the exercise: move behaviour close to data, remove navigation code, and split up a god class. The public client behaviour and assertions were preserved, but assertions now check the objects that own the relevant state.) Tj
ET
endstream
endobj
7 0 obj
<< /Type /Page /Parent 2 0 R /MediaBox [0 0 612 792] /Resources << /Font << /F1 3 0 R >> >> /Contents 6 0 R >>
endobj
8 0 obj
<< /Length 1169 >>
stream
BT
/F1 12 Tf
72 760 Td
16 TL
(2. Changes Made) Tj
T*
(Account now owns account-specific behaviour. Opening an account for a customer, adding funds, applying interest, and closing an account are implemented on Account. Bank still records which accounts are active, but it delegates balance and lifecycle changes to Account.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Branch now owns branch-specific behaviour. The default opening time is stored on the Branch, and Branch provides methods for changing the opening time, adding staff, transferring one staff member, and transferring all staff to another branch. Closing a branch in Bank now delegates the staff movement to Branch before removing the branch from the bank registry.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Customer now owns customer contact details. Default address and phone number are initialised inside Customer instead of being stored in dictionaries on Bank. The client now reads the default contact details from the Customer object directly.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Payroll now exposes a change_payroll_date method. This removes navigation code from Bank, because Bank no longer reaches through Payroll to obtain a PaySchedule and mutate it directly.) Tj
ET
endstream
endobj
9 0 obj
<< /Type /Page /Parent 2 0 R /MediaBox [0 0 612 792] /Resources << /Font << /F1 3 0 R >> >> /Contents 8 0 R >>
endobj
10 0 obj
<< /Length 994 >>
stream
BT
/F1 12 Tf
72 760 Td
16 TL
(3. Rationale) Tj
T*
(The refactoring reduces coupling by making each class responsible for the state it owns. Bank remains useful as a coordinator and registry for branches, accounts, customers, and payroll, but it no longer needs to know the implementation details of account balances, branch staffing, contact details, or pay schedules.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This design is easier to evolve. For example, changing interest calculation now affects Account only, changing branch opening rules affects Branch only, and changing payroll date behaviour affects Payroll only. The client code also becomes clearer because it asks the domain object that owns the state rather than asking Bank for everything.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The refactoring was intentionally small and conservative. No new external dependencies were added, PaySchedule and Staff were left unchanged as requested, and the existing regression test still passes after the client assertions were updated.) Tj
ET
endstream
endobj
